Data

1. For this homework, we will use two different data sets. Please load amniota and amphibio.

amniota data:
Myhrvold N, Baldridge E, Chan B, Sivam D, Freeman DL, Ernest SKM (2015). An amniote life-history database to perform comparative analyses with birds, mammals, and reptiles. Ecology, 96, 3109. doi: 10.1890/15-0846.1 (URL: https://doi.org/10.1890/15-0846.1).

amniota <- read.csv("data/amniota.csv") %>% clean_names()

amphibio data:
Oliveira BF, So-Pedro VA, Santos-Barrera G, Penone C, Costa GC (2017). AmphiBIO, a global database for amphibian ecological traits. Scientific Data, 4, 170123. doi: 10.1038/sdata.2017.123 (URL: https://doi.org/10.1038/sdata.2017.123).

amphibio <- read.csv("data/amphibio.csv") %>% clean_names()

4. How many total NAs are in each data set? Do these values make sense? Are NAs represented by values? These values almost dont seem to make sense. amniota seems to have no NAs, while amphibio seems to have a ridiculous number of NAs. Its likely that amniota uses numbers to represent NA, while amphibio uses NA to encode some other information.

5. Make any necessary replacements in the data such that all NAs appear as NA.

amniota <- amniota %>% 
  replace_with_na_all(condition = ~.x %in% c(common_na_strings, common_na_numbers))
amphibio <- amphibio %>% 
  replace_with_na_all(condition = ~.x %in% c(common_na_strings, common_na_numbers))

8. For the amniota data, calculate the number of NAs in the egg_mass_g column sorted by taxonomic class; i.e.how many NAs are present in the egg_mass_g column in birds, mammals, and reptiles? Does this results make sense biologically? How do these results affect your interpretation of NAs?
This does make sense. Birds are probably the easiest to find eggs of (in nests) while reptiles might be more difficult (if buried). Mammals dont lay eggs, with the exception of the platapus (to my knowledge).

amniota %>% 
  select(class, egg_mass_g) %>% 
  group_by(class) %>% 
  miss_var_summary()

9. The amphibio data have variables that classify species as fossorial (burrowing), terrestrial, aquatic, or arboreal.Calculate the number of NAs in each of these variables. Do you think that the authors intend us to think that there are NAs in these columns or could they represent something else? Explain. By checking the data, and by checking these numbers, it seems that the scientists who made these data used NA to mean false while 1 is meant to mean true. It seems unlikely that a yes/no question would have these many unknowns.

amphibio %>% 
  select(fos, ter, aqu, arb) %>% 
  summarize(across(everything(), ~ sum(is.na(.))))
